      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, thank you for bringing this up — energy struggles on long runs are genuinely frustrating, especially when you're putting in the kind of work you've been doing lately. That 26km last Friday at a solid, consistent effort? That takes real commitment. It makes complete sense that you're looking for answers.\n\nI want to be straightforward with you about two things you've raised, because I care about getting this right for you.\n\n**On the meal plan and keto:** Nutrition planning — especially something as specific as a ketogenic approach — is genuinely outside my lane as a running coach. Prescribing a dietary plan isn't something I'm qualified to do, and I wouldn't want to steer you wrong on something that matters this much. What I'd strongly encourage is booking a session with a **sports registered dietitian**, ideally one who works with endurance athletes. They can look at your whole picture and give you personalised guidance.\n\nWhat I *can* share is some general context on fat adaptation and marathon running, if that would be useful — but I'd want to hear what you already know about it first. What's your understanding of how keto is supposed to help?\n\n**On the light-headedness:** I have to be honest — that one I can't coach around. Light-headedness after runs, combined with wondering about iron, is something a **GP or sports medicine doctor** needs to assess. It could be any number of things, and a simple blood panel can tell you a lot. Please don't put that one off.\n\nOnce you've had that checked out, I'm absolutely here to look at your training load and fueling *timing* — which is very much in my world, and which can make a real difference to how you feel on those long runs.\n\nWhat's been your fueling strategy during the long runs themselves — are you taking anything on board during the effort?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_016dcnQDdnSVJpyfDXZbjnHU"
    }
  ],
